
1. Introduction

Traditional football analytics relies on aggregate statistics such as goals scored, expected goals, or possession. While these metrics provide valuable insights, they fail to capture the dynamic nature of matches.

A football match is inherently a sequential process where the outcome depends on how teams navigate intermediate situations. Therefore, this project models matches as stochastic processes, where each situation is represented as a state and transitions occur over time.

The core idea is:

Performance is determined by the ability of a team to transform game states into favorable absorbing outcomes (win, draw, loss).

To formalize this, we use an absorbing Markov chain framework, allowing us to estimate outcome probabilities from any game state.

2. Data Reconstruction

The first step consists of reconstructing match dynamics from event-level data.

Let:

Gt(i)G_t^{(i)}Gt(i)​ be the number of goals scored by team iii up to time ttt
Ct(i)C_t^{(i)}Ct(i)​ be the number of goals conceded

We define the live score difference as:

Dt(i)=Gt(i)−Ct(i)D_t^{(i)} = G_t^{(i)} - C_t^{(i)}Dt(i)​=Gt(i)​−Ct(i)​

This quantity evolves over time through goal events.

To ensure consistency, we verify that:

GT(i)=Gofficial(i),CT(i)=Cofficial(i)G_T^{(i)} = G_{\text{official}}^{(i)}, \quad C_T^{(i)} = C_{\text{official}}^{(i)}GT(i)​=Gofficial(i)​,CT(i)​=Cofficial(i)​

This validation step guarantees that the reconstructed process matches the final match outcome.

3. State Space Construction

Each match is discretized into states defined by:

score difference Dt∈{−2,−1,0,+1,+2}D_t \in \{-2, -1, 0, +1, +2\}Dt​∈{−2,−1,0,+1,+2}
time bucket Tt∈{T1,T2,T3,T4}T_t \in \{T1, T2, T3, T4\}Tt​∈{T1,T2,T3,T4}

Thus, each state is:

St=(Dt,Tt)S_t = (D_t, T_t)St​=(Dt​,Tt​)

The total number of transient states is:

∣S∣=5×4=20|S| = 5 \times 4 = 20∣S∣=5×4=20

Additionally, we define three absorbing states:

A={Win,Draw,Loss}\mathcal{A} = \{\text{Win}, \text{Draw}, \text{Loss}\}A={Win,Draw,Loss}

4. Transition Dynamics

We model the evolution of the match as a Markov process:

P(St+1=j∣St=i,St−1,…)=P(St+1=j∣St=i)P(S_{t+1} = j \mid S_t = i, S_{t-1}, \ldots) = P(S_{t+1} = j \mid S_t = i)P(St+1​=j∣St​=i,St−1​,…)=P(St+1​=j∣St​=i)

This is the Markov assumption, which states that the future depends only on the current state.

Transitions are observed empirically from data:

Nij=number of transitions from state i to jN_{ij} = \text{number of transitions from state } i \text{ to } jNij​=number of transitions from state i to j

We estimate transition probabilities as:

Pij=Nij∑kNikP_{ij} = \frac{N_{ij}}{\sum_{k} N_{ik}}Pij​=∑k​Nik​Nij​​

5. Absorbing Markov Chain

We partition the transition matrix PPP into:

P=[QR0I]P = \begin{bmatrix} Q & R \\ 0 & I \end{bmatrix}P=[Q0​RI​]

Where:

QQQ: transitions between transient states
RRR: transitions from transient to absorbing states

5.1 Fundamental Matrix

The fundamental matrix is defined as:

N=(I−Q)−1N = (I - Q)^{-1}N=(I−Q)−1

This matrix represents the expected number of visits to each transient state before absorption.

5.2 Absorption Probabilities

The key quantity is:

B=NRB = N RB=NR

Where:

Bij=P(absorption in state j∣starting from state i)B_{ij} = P(\text{absorption in state } j \mid \text{starting from state } i)Bij​=P(absorption in state j∣starting from state i)

Thus, for any game state iii, we can compute:

P(Win∣S=i),P(Draw∣S=i),P(Loss∣S=i)P(\text{Win} \mid S = i), \quad P(\text{Draw} \mid S = i), \quad P(\text{Loss} \mid S = i)P(Win∣S=i),P(Draw∣S=i),P(Loss∣S=i)

6. Team-Level Modeling

The previous framework is applied to each team individually.

For team kkk, we estimate:

Pij(k)=Nij(k)∑lNil(k)P_{ij}^{(k)} = \frac{N_{ij}^{(k)}}{\sum_{l} N_{il}^{(k)}}Pij(k)​=∑l​Nil(k)​Nij(k)​​

However, when the number of observations is small, these estimates become unstable.

7. Shrinkage and Regularization

To address this issue, we introduce a shrinkage estimator:

p^ij(k)=ni(k)⋅pij(k)+λ⋅pij(global)ni(k)+λ\hat{p}_{ij}^{(k)} = \frac{n_i^{(k)} \cdot p_{ij}^{(k)} + \lambda \cdot p_{ij}^{(\text{global})}}{n_i^{(k)} + \lambda}p^​ij(k)​=ni(k)​+λni(k)​⋅pij(k)​+λ⋅pij(global)​​

Where:

ni(k)n_i^{(k)}ni(k)​: number of observations from state iii
pij(global)p_{ij}^{(\text{global})}pij(global)​: global transition probability
λ\lambdaλ: regularization parameter

Justification

This estimator is a form of Bayesian shrinkage, where:

the team-specific estimate is the likelihood
the global estimate acts as a prior

This reduces variance at the cost of a small bias, improving overall stability.

8. Feature Engineering

From the absorption matrix BBB, we construct interpretable performance metrics.

8.1 Open Game Performance

Defined as:

OpenGamek=1∣T∣∑t∈{T1,T2,T3,T4}P(Win∣S=(0,t))\text{OpenGame}_k = \frac{1}{|T|} \sum_{t \in \{T1,T2,T3,T4\}} P(\text{Win} \mid S = (0,t))OpenGamek​=∣T∣1​t∈{T1,T2,T3,T4}∑​P(Win∣S=(0,t))

8.2 Resilience

Resiliencek=1∣T∣∑t[P(Win∣S=(−1,t))+P(Draw∣S=(−1,t))]\text{Resilience}_k = \frac{1}{|T|} \sum_{t} \left[ P(\text{Win} \mid S = (-1,t)) + P(\text{Draw} \mid S = (-1,t)) \right]Resiliencek​=∣T∣1​t∑​[P(Win∣S=(−1,t))+P(Draw∣S=(−1,t))]

8.3 Game Management

Managementk=1∣T∣∑tP(Win∣S=(+1,t))\text{Management}_k = \frac{1}{|T|} \sum_{t} P(\text{Win} \mid S = (+1,t))Managementk​=∣T∣1​t∑​P(Win∣S=(+1,t))

8.4 Clutch Performance

Clutchk=P(Win∣S=(+1,T4))\text{Clutch}_k = P(\text{Win} \mid S = (+1,T4))Clutchk​=P(Win∣S=(+1,T4))

9. Statistical Analysis

We evaluate the relationship between these metrics and total points using Spearman correlation:

ρ(X,Y)=corrSpearman(X,Y)\rho(X, Y) = \text{corr}_{\text{Spearman}}(X, Y)ρ(X,Y)=corrSpearman​(X,Y)

Results:

OpenGame → ρ≈0.939\rho \approx 0.939ρ≈0.939
Management → ρ≈0.636\rho \approx 0.636ρ≈0.636
Clutch → ρ≈0.646\rho \approx 0.646ρ≈0.646
Resilience → ρ≈0.554\rho \approx 0.554ρ≈0.554

Interpretation

The dominance of OpenGame suggests that:

Performance≈f(ability to win neutral states)\text{Performance} \approx f(\text{ability to win neutral states})Performance≈f(ability to win neutral states)

10. Timing Analysis

We define:

Δopen=P(Win∣(0,T4))−P(Win∣(0,T1))\Delta_{\text{open}} = P(\text{Win} \mid (0,T4)) - P(\text{Win} \mid (0,T1))Δopen​=P(Win∣(0,T4))−P(Win∣(0,T1))

Observed:

Δopen<0\Delta_{\text{open}} < 0Δopen​<0

Interpretation

Strong teams have:

P(Win∣(0,T1))>P(Win∣(0,T4))P(\text{Win} \mid (0,T1)) > P(\text{Win} \mid (0,T4))P(Win∣(0,T1))>P(Win∣(0,T4))

Meaning they are more effective early in matches.

11. PCA (Dimensionality Reduction)

We apply PCA to the feature matrix XXX:

Z=XWZ = XWZ=XW

Where:

WWW: eigenvectors of covariance matrix

Interpretation

PC1 → overall strength
PC2 → resilience vs management
PC3 → open game
PC4 → clutch

12. Clustering

We apply K-means:

min⁡C∑k=1K∑i∈Ck∥xi−μk∥2\min_{C} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{i \in C_k} \|x_i - \mu_k\|^2Cmin​k=1∑K​i∈Ck​∑​∥xi​−μk​∥2

Result

Teams cluster into:

dominant
balanced
weak

13. Why Teams Lose Points

We define:

FailOpenk=1−OpenGamek\text{FailOpen}_k = 1 - \text{OpenGame}_kFailOpenk​=1−OpenGamek​ LoseLeadk=1−Managementk\text{LoseLead}_k = 1 - \text{Management}_kLoseLeadk​=1−Managementk​ FailResiliencek=1−Resiliencek\text{FailResilience}_k = 1 - \text{Resilience}_kFailResiliencek​=1−Resiliencek​

Key Result

FailOpen≫LoseLead,FailResilience\text{FailOpen} \gg \text{LoseLead}, \text{FailResilience}FailOpen≫LoseLead,FailResilience

Interpretation

The main reason teams lose points is:

failure to convert neutral states into wins\text{failure to convert neutral states into wins}failure to convert neutral states into wins

14. Conclusion

This project demonstrates that football performance can be effectively modeled using an absorbing Markov framework.

The main result is:

Performance≈Ability to win from neutral states\text{Performance} \approx \text{Ability to win from neutral states}Performance≈Ability to win from neutral states

Strong teams do not necessarily excel in all dimensions, but they consistently convert open situations into victories.

Conversely, weaker teams do not primarily lose points due to collapse or lack of resilience, but because they fail to take the lead.
